Vladimir Putin and the Risk of a Third World War
San Francisco — On February 24, Russia's invasion of Ukraine marked the beginning of a third world war that could destroy our civilization.
Before the invasion, Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping held a lengthy meeting on February 4 — the day that marked the beginning of the Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympic Games.
After the meeting, the two leaders issued a carefully drafted document of 5,000 words announcing the establishment of a close partnership between the two countries.
This document is more powerful than any treaty and certainly required extensive prior negotiations.
I am shocked that Xi seems to have fully entrusted Putin with invading and launching the war in Ukraine.
He viewed the confirmation of his becoming a lifelong ruler of China in the second half of this year as merely a formality, and he was certainly confident about it.
After concentrating all power in his own hands, Xi carefully devised a plan to elevate himself to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
With Xi's support, Putin set out to realize his lifelong dream in an incredibly brutal manner.
At nearly 70 years old, Putin felt that if he wanted to leave a significant mark in Russian history, it had to be now or never.
But his view of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
He seems to believe that the Russian people need a tsar whom they can blindly follow.
This system is the opposite of a democratic society, and this vision distorts the "soul" of the emotionally sensitive Russian people.
As a child, I had a lot of contact with Russian soldiers who occupied Hungary in 1945.
I know that if you asked them for something, they would share their last piece of bread with you.
Later, in the early 1980s, I began what I call my political charitable work.
At first, I established a foundation in my homeland Hungary, and then I actively participated in activities that contributed to the dissolution of the Soviet empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, this dissolution had already begun.
I also established a foundation in Russia, and then in each of the republics that became independent.
In Ukraine, I established a foundation even before it became an independent country.
I also visited China in 1984 and became the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation there (I closed this foundation in 1989, shortly before the Tiananmen Square massacre occurred).
I personally do not know Putin, but I have closely watched his rise and fully understand his ruthless character.
He leveled the capital of Chechnya, Grozny, and now he threatens to do the same to Kyiv, the capital of Ukraine.
Putin was a shrewd KGB agent, but he seems to have changed recently.
He seems to have lost touch with reality because he has developed a fixed mindset.
Without a doubt, he misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He had assumed that Russian-speaking Ukrainians would welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but it turned out they were no different from those who spoke Ukrainian.
Faced with what seemed to be a one-sided possibility, the Ukrainian people still carried out an incredible act of brave resistance.
In July 2021, Putin published a long article stating that Russians and Ukrainians are actually one nation, and that Ukrainians had been misled by neo-Nazi agitators.
Because Kyiv is the original site of the Russian Orthodox Church, the first part of his argument is not without historical basis.
But in the content of Part 2, it is Putin who was misled.
He should have known the facts more clearly.
Many Ukrainians bravely fought in the Euromaidan protests that erupted in 2014.
The 2014 events made him very angry.
But when ordered to attack his Ukrainian brothers, the Russian army performed poorly.
The deeply rooted corruption in the defense ministry's contract awarding process also played a significant role in this poor performance.
But instead of blaming himself, Putin seemed to have lost his mind.
He was determined to punish Ukraine for resisting him, and his actions seemed to be completely unchecked.
He threw the entire Russian army into battle and ignored all rules of engagement, especially the indiscriminate bombing of civilian populations.
Many hospitals were attacked, and the power grid supplying the Chernobyl nuclear plant (currently occupied by Russian forces) was also destroyed.
In besieged Mariupol, as many as 400,000 people have had no water or food for nearly a week.
Russia is likely to lose this war.
The United States and the European Union are both sending defensive weapons to Ukraine, while also trying to purchase Russian-made MIG fighters that Ukrainian pilots know how to operate.
These could change the entire situation.
Regardless of the outcome, Putin has already created a miracle in strengthening European resolve and unity.
At the same time, Xi seems to have realized that Putin has been unfaithful.
On March 8, after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi insisted that Sino-Russian friendship remains "as solid as a rock," Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz, expressing his support for their peacekeeping efforts.
To avoid a humanitarian crisis, he hopes for maximum restraint in the war.
It is still fundamentally uncertain whether Putin will accommodate Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be removed from power before they destroy our civilization.
